<br>
When he was 19 years old, he informed his parents that he would be leaving the city... not for good, but for a long time perhaps.  &quot;Why?&quot;, his mother asked, &quot;Why would you leave your home?&quot;  Tamazar replied confidently, &quot;Mother, I wish to fight for the honor of our city.&quot;  There had never been a High Elf that was born with the blood of a Warrior, &quot;Could he be the one?&quot;, his mother thought to herself.  She was in awe at the unusually large stature of her only son, she herself was an Enchantress of Tunare and his father a very powerful Wizard.<br>
<br>
Tamazar gathered his belongings from their small house, kissed his mother goodbye and walked out the door.  The tension that had been in his mother's mind before he left quickly vanished, as now she felt like he had forgotten something.  &quot;Of course,&quot;, she thought out loud, &quot;money!!!&quot;  She quickly ran to her own small bedroom, reached into a hidden compartment in the wall, and removed a small leather purse full of Platinum pieces.  She ran from the house towards the city gates to meet her son there to ensure that he would have enough money to buy needed supplies for his journey.<br>
<br>
Tamazar slowed as he came to the gate and saw his mother, whom he had just left a few minutes ago.  Without a word, she handed him the purse, hugged him, and walked back home.  &quot;Mother, I shall return!&quot;, cried Tamazar as she slowly walked away.  He left the city gates somewhat saddened by the previous events.  Upon reaching the wooded area just outside the city limits, Tamazar pulled out his hatchet and began looking for deadfall trees to chop and use as firewood.  &quot;If only I had father's skill,&quot; he thought to himself, &quot;I wouldn't need wood for a fire at all.&quot;  Tamazar found a suitable tree, a birch, known throughout Felwithe as the best type of tree for building a fire.  As he was taught as a small boy, he stacked the newly chopped wood, and removed two small rocks from his pocket.  He smacked the rocks together repeatedly, causing sparks to fly from his hands and into the pile of wood.  Eventually, the sparks caught the wood on fire, and Tamazar sat, thinking about his journey ahead.<br>
<br>
In the morning, Tamazar awoke to the sound of birds chirping in the distance.  &quot;A more beautiful day, I have never seen.&quot; he said to himself, and began collecting his gear once again.  He opened his backpack and pulled out a hand sewn leather tunic, leather pants, and a short sword.  Having made sure his fire was extinguished, he began walking deeper into the woods.  He was unsure of where he was headed, as he had never left the city before last night.  He continued walking however, and eventually found monsters in his path.<br>
<br>
They were like nothing he had ever seen before.  As he was still quite far away, they hadn't seen him yet, but he was unsure how long it would be before they did catch a glimpse of his movement.  He sat again, and removed a large book from his backpack.  He opened to the first page, and it was blank.  He removed the enchanted quill his mother had given him from the bindings of the book and placed the point of the quill on the page.  On its own, the quill began dancing all over the page, copying the image in Tamazar's head.  It drew the monster exactly as Tamazar had seen them, and stood completely still on the page when it was finished.  He replaced the quill and the book, stood up, and slowly moved toward the two ugly creatures.<br>
<br>
As he crept nearer to the creatures, he could hear them 'talking'... but he couldn't understand a word of what they were saying.  Suddenly, he stepped on a branch and the monsters snapped their heads in his direction.  They began running towards him shouting unknown obsenities about Tamazar, and he drew his short sword from it's sheath and began defending against the attackers.  He blocked slash after slash from the two vile creatures and quickly reached over his own shoulder and pulled from his pack a chained mace.  Swinging from the backpack, the head of the mace came crashing down on the first monster's head, killing it instantly.  The second fell soon after from the same force.<br>
<br>
In his rush of adrenaline, Tamazar failed to notice that he had been cut by one of the creatures.  He bent down to pick up the change he found near one of the creatures' corpses and the sight of the blood on his arm made him grasp the wound tightly.  A warming calm came immediately over him, and when he removed his hand from the wound, it was gone.  Not even a scar remained.  &quot;What is this?&quot; Tamazar wondered.  Never had this happened to him before, and it scared him greatly.  He began to break into a full run towards his home town of Felwithe once again, and entered into the guild of High Priests.<br>
<br>
